Description: A Phoenician amphora of compact pale pink marlware pottery, with a rounded base, and bulbous body. Two handles are attached near the top, at the level of the angular shoulder. There was a short cylindrical neck, but most of this has been broken off and is missing. The jar is inscribed on one side with three lines of hieratic text in black paint. The exterior is covered by a pale cream-yellow slip, most of which still remains although there has been some loss. The fabric contains small chips of limestone.
Findspot: Excavated/Findspot: Tell Dafana, "Qasr", east annex (C), chamber 11
Curator's comments: The Findspot number 11 has been scratched into the shoulder of the vessel.
Bibliographic references: Leclère and Spencer 2014 / Tell Dafana Reconsidered: The Archaeology of an Egyptian Frontier Town (p.112, p.116, p.199, pl.41, p.221, pl.63)
